>
  <p>A word scrambler randomly rearranges letters in words — used for word games, puzzles, and demonstrating the psychology of reading. TextWonder offers three scramble modes: middle-letter, full, and word order.</p>

  <h2>How to Scramble Words</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Type or paste your text.</li>
    <li>Choose a scramble mode: <strong>Middle Letters</strong>, <strong>Full Scramble</strong>, or <strong>Scramble Word Order</strong>.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Scramble</strong>.</li>
    <li>Click again for a new random scramble.</li>
    <li>Copy the result.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>The Interesting Science Behind Middle-Letter Scramble</h2>
  <p>Studies (including the famous Cambridge University reading experiment) found that readers can still understand sentences when the internal letters of words are scrambled — because the brain reads words as a whole pattern, not letter by letter. The first and last letters are the anchor points.</p>

  <h2>Use Cases</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Creating word puzzles and games</li>
    <li>Educational activities for children</li>
    <li>Demonstrating cognitive science concepts</li>
    <li>Fun scrambled-message social media posts</li>
  </ul>

